{
    "analysis": "The Executor loaded the four telemetry files and returned a compact summary. Key observations: metric, trace, and log data cover 2024-01-20 15:33:00 to 2024-01-20 15:57:00 UTC, which is inside the incident window (2024-01-20 15:30:28 to 2024-01-20 16:00:28 UTC). error_logs.csv is empty. metric.csv has 1710 rows with frequent KPIs including cpu, socket, mem, latency-90, latency-50, workload, diskio. trace.csv and log.csv also have many entries; trace names indicate spans between frontend, checkout, and productcatalog services. Since metrics exist for many services and cover the incident period, the next step is metric-based anomaly detection: compute global thresholds per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the full available series (e.g., P95), then inspect data points within the incident window to find anomalies (points exceeding P95). This will narrow candidate faulty components/KPIs for subsequent trace and log analysis. No root cause determined yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, do the following in code: 1) For each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute the global P95 threshold of the full available 'value' series (do NOT filter by incident window when computing this). 2) Filter metric.csv to rows within the incident window 2024-01-20 15:30:28 to 2024-01-20 16:00:28 UTC (convert timestamps with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True) for comparison). 3) For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) produce a compact aggregate with these columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95_threshold, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count (points in window with value >= p95_threshold), earliest_anomaly_utc (UTC datetime of the first anomaly in window) or NaT if none, and max_value_in_window. 4) Return the rows sorted by anomaly_count descending and limit to top 20 rows. Keep the output compact (only the requested columns and up to 20 rows)." }

{
    "analysis": "The previous metric analysis computed global P95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) and then inspected the incident window. Findings: widespread 'socket' KPI anomalies across many services (currencyservice, cartservice, adservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice, paymentservice, redis, shippingservice, etc.). Some services also show diskio anomalies (p95=0), and adservice shows a few mem/cpu/latency anomalies. error_logs.csv is empty. This indicates a broad network/socket-related problem affecting many services during the window, but multiple services are flagged so we cannot yet pick the single root-cause component. According to the diagnosis workflow, we should now use traces to localize the most downstream faulty service among the metric-flagged services. Traces (trace.csv) include service-to-service span metrics (duration_p95/duration_mean/error_rate/row_count) which can help identify which service is the last faulty service in call chains. We need a compact aggregate of trace anomalies within the same incident window (using global P95 thresholds computed from the full trace series) to prioritize candidate faulty services.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv only, do the following: 1) For each unique (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute the global P95 threshold of the full 'value' series (do NOT filter by incident window when computing this). 2) Convert timestamps to UTC datetimes and filter rows within the incident window 2024-01-20 15:30:28 to 2024-01-20 16:00:28 UTC. 3) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) produce a compact aggregate with these columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, p95_threshold, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count (points in window with value >= p95_threshold), earliest_anomaly_utc (UTC datetime of first anomaly in window) or NaT if none, and max_value_in_window. 4) Return the rows sorted by anomaly_count descending and limit to top 20 rows. Keep the output compact (only the requested columns and up to 20 rows)."
}

{
    "analysis": "The trace analysis shows many trace.error_rate series with global P95 = 0.0, which saturates the anomaly detector (every point >= 0) and is not actionable. Therefore we cannot rely on trace.error_rate anomalies. Metric analysis earlier showed widespread 'socket' KPI anomalies across many services (including the provided candidate services currencyservice, checkoutservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice), pointing to a network/socket-level problem. To localize the root service we should use trace duration metrics (duration_mean / duration_p95) which are less likely to have zero P95 and can indicate which service in the call chain experienced latency or degradation. We need a compact ranking of trace duration series that show significant deviation from their global P95 (e.g., high max / p95 ratio) within the incident window to identify the most downstream faulty service. No final root cause yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv only, do the following: 1) Restrict to trace_name values that contain 'duration' (e.g., 'duration_mean' or 'duration_p95'). 2) For each unique (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute the global P95 threshold from the full series (do NOT filter by window). 3) Convert timestamps to UTC datetimes and filter rows within the incident window 2024-01-20 15:30:28 to 2024-01-20 16:00:28 UTC. 4) For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) produce a compact aggregate with: cmdb_id, trace_name, p95_threshold, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count (points in window with value >= p95_threshold), earliest_anomaly_utc (first anomaly in window or NaT), max_value_in_window, and ratio = max_value_in_window / p95_threshold (set ratio to NaN if p95_threshold == 0). 5) Return rows where total_points_in_window > 0, sorted by ratio descending, limited to top 20. Keep output compact (only requested columns and up to 20 rows)."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace-duration analysis identified the largest relative latency spikes involving currencyservice (root→currencyservice and currencyservice.from_root) with a very high ratio (~58x for duration_p95) and first anomalies at ~2024-01-20 15:54:00 UTC. Smaller spikes appear on checkout↔payment paths (~15:39 UTC). Metric analysis earlier showed widespread 'socket' KPI anomalies across many services starting ~15:33 UTC, suggesting a broad network/socket-level problem. Traces point to currencyservice as the most significant downstream latency outlier within the window, but many services show socket anomalies so we need logs to confirm whether currencyservice (or another candidate) shows error or traffic degradation consistent with a network/socket failure. error_logs.csv is empty, so use log.csv. The next step is to check logs for the provided candidate services (checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice) by computing global P95 per (cmdb_id,log_name) from the full series, then inspecting the incident window for anomalies (value >= P95 and also look for drops in row_count). This will help confirm the root component and whether socket/network errors correlate with currencyservice latency spikes.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using log.csv only, do the following in code: 1) Restrict analysis to these candidate services: checkoutservice, currencyservice, emailservice, productcatalogservice, recommendationservice. 2) For each unique (cmdb_id, log_name) among those services compute the global P95 threshold from the full available 'value' series (do NOT filter by the incident window when computing P95). 3) Convert timestamps to UTC datetimes and filter rows within the incident window 2024-01-20 15:30:28 to 2024-01-20 16:00:28 UTC. 4) For each (cmdb_id, log_name) produce a compact aggregate with columns: cmdb_id, log_name, p95_threshold, total_points_in_window, anomaly_count (points in window with value >= p95_threshold), earliest_anomaly_utc (UTC datetime of first anomaly in window or NaT), and max_value_in_window. 5) Also compute for any 'log.row_count' series whether there are any values in-window below P15 (15th percentile) of the full series (compute global P15) and report count and earliest timestamp if present. 6) Return results sorted by anomaly_count descending, limit to top 20 rows, and keep the output compact (only the requested columns and up to 20 rows)."
}

